{
  "card_id": "t_spot",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "T-Spot",
  "aliases": [
    "EQ Zone",
    "eq zone",
    "Equilibrium Spot",
    "equilibrium spot",
    "Higher time frame wick formation zone",
    "higher time frame wick formation zone",
    "t-pot",
    "T-Pot",
    "t-spot area",
    "T-Spot area"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A zone marked on a higher timeframe candle (typically C2/C3/C4) where the next candle's wick is expected before expansion. It is often the 50% equilibrium of the prior candle's range or the upper/lower half of candle 3's range, used as a precise entry area for continuation within the fractal model.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Confirm a higher timeframe candle 2 closure (sweeping a prior high/low and closing back inside its range) and a change in state of delivery through opposing candle series; this establishes the directional bias.",
    "Identify the T-Spot as the 50% equilibrium of the prior candle’s range, or the indicator-marked upper (bearish) / lower (bullish) half of candle 3’s range. Alternatively, if no fair value gap or swing point exists, use the 50% level of a series of consecutive down/up close candles.",
    "Price must retrace into the T-Spot and form a wick; a valid reaction requires a point of interest (fair value gap, order block, or swing high/low) within the zone and confirmation via a change in state of delivery on the relevant lower time frame.",
    "The T-Spot is invalidated if price closes beyond the zone against the bias direction; a deeper retracement or new phase of delivery should be expected.",
    "In bearish setups, the T-Spot marks the area where price is expected to rise to form a high; in bullish setups, it marks the area where price is expected to drop to form a low.",
    "The T-Spot can be customized in indicators via color (default gray and green)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The T-Spot is used to wait for a retracement entry after directional bias is confirmed. Traders anticipate a wick formation inside the zone, then enter on a confirming change in state of delivery (e.g., breaking through opposing candle series or reacting off a PD array/fair value gap) with a stop beyond the T-Spot extreme. Targets include the next draw on liquidity, previous day high/low, or standard deviation projections, typically aiming for at least 2R. Overlapping T-Spots on multiple timeframes provides high-probability confluence.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering prematurely before price fully retraces into the T-Spot and forms a wick, or before a confirming change in state of delivery.",
    "Trading against the higher time frame directional bias or ignoring contextual confluence (sweep, closure, draw on liquidity).",
    "Entering solely on the higher time frame T-Spot without confirming a lower time frame fractal setup.",
    "Applying the T-Spot on very low time frames (e.g., 5-minute) where the signal becomes noisy and less reliable.",
    "Entering the T-Spot without a clear point of interest (fair value gap, swing high/low, order block) inside the zone.",
    "Preferring the T-Spot when a valid fair value gap or order block is already present, which offers better risk-to-reward.",
    "Expecting expansion when price closes through the T-Spot level, invalidating the setup, or after price has returned to prior targets.",
    "Confusing a consolidation move with a valid retracement into the T-Spot.",
    "Taking the T-Spot entry after three or more expansion candles, when a new phase of delivery (consolidation, retracement, or reversal) is more likely.",
    "Taking positional entries when the T-Spot is too wide, leading to poor risk-to-reward due to a large stop distance.",
    "Trading back into the range off a large wick instead of waiting for the following cleaner candle.",
    "Entering on a marginal close just barely beyond a candle rather than waiting for a clear close over the full candle.",
    "Ignoring the timeframe filter settings, causing the T-Spot to display in unsuitable trading sessions, reducing signal quality.",
    "Failing to hide higher timeframe candles when overlapping with lower timeframe setups, causing chart clutter and misjudgment of price action."
  ],
